        ", where he served as chief of staff.     Bormann used his position to create an extensive bureaucracy and involve himself as much as possible in the decision making. He gained acceptance into Hitlers inner circle, and accompanied him everywhere, providing briefings and summaries of events and requests. He began acting as Hitlers personal secretary on 12 August 1935. Bormann assumed Hess former duties, with the title of Head of the Parteikanzlei , after Hess solo flight to Britain on 10 May 1941 to seek peace negotiations with the British government. He had final approval over civil service appointments, reviewed and approved legislation, and by 1943 had de facto control over all domestic matters. Bormann was one of the leading proponents of the ongoing persecution of the Christian churches and favoured harsh treatment of ": null
